# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: x11-windowing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] A **compositing manager**, or **compositor**, is software that provides applications with an off-screen buffer for each window, then composites these window buffers into an image representing the screen and writes the result into the display memory.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] A **compositing window manager** is a window manager that is also a compositing manager.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Computer graphics technology allows for visual effects to be rendered in real time such as drop shadows, live previews, and complex animation.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Since the screen is double buffered, it does not flicker during updates.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] The window manager sends each window a message to repaint itself when needed.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] When a window in front is moved, it can reveal an area of a window behind that was previously concealed.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Window managers are broadly categorised by their strategy for causing that newly revealed area to be displayed to the user.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] In the "stacking" strategy, the window manager tells the back window to repaint itself.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] In the "compositing" strategy, the window manager maintains an off-screen memory buffer containing the full appearance of each window, including the back window.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] With a stacking manager, the repainting process can become corrupted when a program that is slow, unresponsive or buggy does not respond to messages in a timely manner.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] A malicious program can cause the system to appear unstable by simply neglecting to repaint its window.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] With a compositing manager, if a window stops repainting itself when requested by the window manager, its last repaint will remain displayed and the window might be dimmed.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Often, the title changes to reflect the status of the window as unresponsive.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] A program may prevent its window from being moved or unmapped, but generally will not cause repainting problems.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] The Commodore Amiga, released in 1985, was one of the first systems with a compositing windowing system.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Applications could first request a region of memory outside the current display region for use as bitmap.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] The Amiga windowing system would then use a series of bit blits using the system's hardware blitter to build a composite of these applications' bitmaps - along with buttons and sliders - in display memory, without requiring these applications to redraw any of their bitmaps.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] On March 24, 2001, Apple's Mac OS X 10.0 (Cheetah) became the first mainstream operating system to feature software-based 3D compositing and effects, provided by its Quartz component.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] With the release of Mac OS X 10.2 (Jaguar) and Quartz Extreme, the job of compositing could move to dedicated graphics hardware.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] In 2003 Sun Microsystems demonstrated an ambitious 3D graphics system called Project Looking Glass to layer on top of its Swing toolkit.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] It was first shown at the 2003 LinuxWorld Expo.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Although Apple threatened to sue Sun for breach of intellectual-property rights, other window managers have implemented some of the functionality in Looking Glass.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] By 2006 development was discontinued by Sun, whose primary business was transitioning from graphically oriented Unix workstations to selling enterprise mainframes.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Microsoft first presented the Desktop Window Manager in Project Longhorn to the 2003 Windows Hardware Engineering Conference, demonstrating wobbly windows.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Severe delays in the Longhorn development process caused Microsoft not to debut its 3D-compositing window-manager until the release of Windows Vista in November 2006.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Implementing compositing under the X Window System required some redesign, which took place incrementally.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Metacity 2.8.4 was released in August 2004.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] However, the first widely publicized compositing window manager for X was Xfwm, released in January 2005.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] On 26 January 2005 Compiz was released, introducing fully accelerated 3D-compositing to the Linux platform.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] In compositing, 3D effects could be applied on windows to provide 3D desktop effects.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Modern compositing window managers use 3D hardware acceleration.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Compositing window manager software communicates with graphics hardware via programming interfaces such as OpenGL or Direct3D.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] The earliest widespread implementations using this technique were released for the Mac in Mac OS X 10.2, and for Linux in a Luminocity prototype.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Currently, window managers using OpenGL include Compiz, KWin, and the Quartz Compositor, while Desktop Window Manager currently uses DirectX 9.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] OpenGL is still not fully supported in hardware, so performance of OpenGL-based compositing should continue to improve as hardware improves.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Stacking window managers running on the X Window System (X11) required a chroma keying or green screening extension.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Compositing was introduced by way of the Composite Extension.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Compositing managers use hardware acceleration through this extension, if available.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Under X11, the ability to do full 3D-accelerated compositing required fundamental changes to the window system protocol in order to use hardware acceleration.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Originally, a number of modified X11 implementations designed around OpenGL began to appear, including Xgl.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] The introduction of AIGLX would eliminate the need to use Xgl, and allow window managers to do 3D accelerated compositing on a standard X server, while still allowing for direct rendering.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Currently, NVIDIA, Intel, and ATI cards support AIGLX.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Compiz introduced a cube effect, which allows the user to see up to 6 virtual desktops at once.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Each desktop is converted into a surface texture of the cube, which can be rotated at will.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Compiz displays a wide array of 2D and 3D effects and has relatively low hardware requirements.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] In 2012, Compiz was included in Ubuntu Linux, and was enabled automatically when supported hardware and drivers were available and the user had not selected 2D Mode.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Mutter (Metacity + Clutter) has replaced Metacity as the default window manager for GNOME.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] It is featured in the GNOME Shell component of GNOME 3.0.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] It uses the display engine Clutter, which has been ported to all major operating systems, netbooks and smartphones.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Since version 4, KDE's window manager KWin has compositing capabilities.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] KWin features much of the same functionality also present in Compiz.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] With the Wayland protocol, a compositing window manager is also a display server; there is no display server separate from the window manager.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] The combined window manager/display server is called a Wayland compositor.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Weston is a reference implementation of a Wayland compositor; KWin and Mutter are also Wayland compositors as well as being X11 compositing window managers.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Project Looking Glass was a window manager combining 3D rendering and the cross-platform Java programming language.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] It is now inactive and released under the GNU General Public License.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] The Granular Linux live CD distribution includes Looking Glass as an optional window manager.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] In the aftermath of it being discontinued, some of its features, such as cover switching and thumbnail live previews, have found their way onto other window managers.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Its more original features included window tilting, two-sided window frames and parallax scrolling backgrounds.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] While they are able to run on 3D-capable hardware, AmigaOS 4 and MorphOS are designed to run on old legacy Amiga computers, starting with the Amiga 1200.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] As such, their window managers have mostly planar rendering capabilities that include composite layering, alpha blending, gradients, high resolution and multiple desktops ("screens") that can partially clip one another.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] While the window manager in Windows 2000 does perform compositing, it does not perform transformations such as a per-pixel alpha.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Few commercial applications took advantage of alpha blending; freeware programs were among the first to experiment with it, albeit through optional settings.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Compositing was introduced with Desktop Window Manager in Windows Vista.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Windows Vista and Windows 7 allow the user to disable Desktop Window Manager by selecting the Windows Basic appearance settings.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] In addition, it is automatically disabled by Windows in order to perform hardware overlay through the Overlay Mixer Filter.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] The compositing approach makes it easier to implement a number of features that make the user interface more accessible, simpler to use or with eye candy elements.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Vector graphics, such as TrueType fonts and 3D-accelerated elements, can be expanded without degradation (usually due to aliasing).
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] A screen magnifier enlarges an area of the screen, making portions of text easier to read – whether to prevent eye strain, for the visually impaired, or simply at a distance.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Zoom effects such as the fish eye magnifier and zoom desktop effects provide this functionality.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] A preview of a window can be displayed in a pop-up thumbnail when the user hovers its associated taskbar button.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] This allows the user to identify and manage several concurrently running programs.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Windows with similar names and icons tend to cause confusion, especially when their title bars overlap; the position of every such window on the taskbar has to be memorized.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] When there are many open windows in this manner, the user often has to resort to trial and error—clicking each taskbar button one-by-one—before proceeding.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Window switching allows one to quickly preview several windows at once by temporarily rearranging them against a decorative background.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] After a selection is made, the windows are then restored to their original arrangement.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Selection begins when the user either enters a hotkey combination, moves the mouse pointer to a hotspot on the screen, or, in some situations, uses the mouse's scroll wheel.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Items are navigated using the keyboard or mouse.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] An item is selected by either releasing the hotkey, hitting the Enter key or clicking on it with the mouse.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] The flip switcher is an enhancement to the Alt-Tab switching feature.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Running windows are arranged into a stack – similar to a flip-style selector in a 1950s jukebox, or a Rolodex.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] In some systems, the user can press Alt-Shift-Tab to navigate backwards.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Visual transitions are applied to each item while navigating.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Common implementations of flip switching include Flip 3D in Windows and Shift Switcher in Compiz.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Cover switching is like flip switching with a few, mostly visual, differences.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Instead of one stack with the selection at the top, two symmetrical stacks are shown with the current selection front and center (similar to the window tilting feature in Looking Glass).
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Cover Flow is an implementation of cover switching in macOS.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] More recent versions use blurring to de-emphasize non-selected items.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Cover Flow has also been implemented in other software published by Apple such as iTunes.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Ring switching is like flip switching, except the windows move in a circle, with the current selection in front, usually at the bottom.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Most compositing window managers include this feature out of the box, and third-party applications, such as 3d-desktop, are also available.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] The user can group windows together, such that only one window at a time is visible in each group.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] In Compiz, the window frame is flipped to indicate when the active window in its group has been changed.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] macOS displays a preview of every window on the screen by tiling them.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Other systems with similar functionality (Microsoft Windows, Compiz, KWin, third-party applications) are referred to as Exposé clones.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] The hotkey to activate Exposé is not Alt-Tab, but rather F3.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Mac OS X 10.7 combines several other compositing features developed by Apple—such as Exposé, Dashboard, and Spaces—into a larger program called Mission Control.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] On macOS, "widgets" (single-purpose applets) such as a clock, note pad, and calculator can appear by pressing a hotkey.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Widget engines speed work by keeping commonly used widgets accessible while unobtrusive.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] They are handled by the Dashboard program in macOS.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Compiz starts with a blank Widget Layer, allowing the user to add applications by clicking on them.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] A variety of widgets are supported, including Screenlets, gDesklets and SuperKaramba.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Windows Vista provides gadgets that the user can place on the Windows Sidebar (Sidebar gadgets), a Windows Live start page (Web gadgets), or an external display, such as the user's mobile phone (SideShow gadgets).
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] The Windows Sidebar was a visible partition in Windows Vista, and was eliminated in Windows 7, along with Sidebar gadgets which were changed to Desktop Gadgets.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Before compositing window managers were developed, windows would instantly jump in and out of view, which is incongruent with the interface metaphor (and with a physical office setting).
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Some systems like the Classic Mac OS avoided this issue with ZoomRects, animating the windows outline "zooming" toward its final position.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] But on most systems, the sudden appearance and disappearance of GUI elements may seem confusing or even chaotic to inexperienced users.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Visual transitions provide context and help distinguish the causal relationships of GUI elements.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Instead of just disappearing, a window may fade away, or visibly shrink to the taskbar.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] A pull-down menu that has been clicked may smoothly radiate outward from the menu bar, making it easier to determine its origin and purpose.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Gradual and natural transitions may be especially helpful for elderly or visually impaired users who notice changes to the screen more slowly and with less clarity.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] For example, an inexperienced user may impulsively click on a menu that was activated by accident, causing him or her to lose work.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] The short delay necessary to display a visual transition may give the user enough time to make a conscious decision, and avoid such mistakes.
[src:x11-windowing/compositing-window-manager] Metisse implements user interface façades, a system that provides users with simple ways to adapt, reconfigure, and recombine existing graphical interfaces, through the use of direct manipulation techniques.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] In a graphical user interface (GUI), a **graphical widget** (also **graphical control element** or **control**) is an element of interaction, such as a button or a scroll bar.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] Controls are software components that a computer user interacts with through direct manipulation to read or edit information about an application.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] User interface libraries such as Windows Presentation Foundation, Qt, GTK, and Cocoa, contain a collection of controls and the logic to render these.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] Each widget facilitates a specific type of user-computer interaction, and appears as a visible part of the application's GUI as defined by the theme and rendered by the rendering engine.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] The theme makes all widgets adhere to a unified aesthetic design and creates a sense of overall cohesion.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] Some widgets support interaction with the user, for example labels, buttons, and check boxes.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] Others act as containers that group the widgets added to them, for example windows, panels, and tabs.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] Structuring a user interface with widget toolkits allows developers to reuse code for similar tasks, and provides users with a common language for interaction, maintaining consistency throughout the whole information system.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] Graphical user interface builders facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] They automatically generate all the source code for a widget from general descriptions provided by the developer, usually through direct manipulation.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] Around 1920, *widget* entered American English, as a generic term for any useful device, particularly a product manufactured for sale; a gadget.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] In 1988, the term *widget* is attested in the context of Project Athena and the X Window System.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] The same year, in the manual *X Toolkit Widgets - C Language X Interface* by Ralph R.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] Finally, still in the same year, Ralph R.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] Any widget displays an information arrangement changeable by the user, such as a window or a text box.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] The defining characteristic of a widget is to provide a single interaction point for the direct manipulation of a given kind of data.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] In other words, widgets are basic visual building blocks which, combined in an application, hold all the data processed by the application and the available interactions on this data.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] GUI widgets are graphical elements used to build the human-machine-interface of a program.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] GUI widgets are implemented like software components.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] Widget toolkits and software frameworks, like e.g.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] GTK+ or Qt, contain them in software libraries so that programmers can use them to build GUIs for their programs.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] A family of common reusable widgets has evolved for holding general information based on the Palo Alto Research Center Inc. research for the Xerox Alto User Interface.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] Various implementations of these generic widgets are often packaged together in widget toolkits, which programmers use to build graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] Most operating systems include a set of ready-to-tailor widgets that a programmer can incorporate in an application, specifying how it is to behave.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] Each type of widget generally is defined as a class by object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] Therefore, many widgets are derived from class inheritance.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] In the context of an application, a widget may be *enabled* or *disabled* at a given point in time.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] An enabled widget has the capacity to respond to events, such as keystrokes or mouse actions.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] A widget that cannot respond to such events is considered disabled.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] The appearance of a widget typically differs depending on whether it is enabled or disabled; when disabled, a widget may be drawn in a lighter color ("**grayed out**") or be obscured visually in some way.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] On pop-up dialogues, buttons might appear greyed out shortly after appearance to prevent accidental clicking or inadvertent double-tapping.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] Widgets are sometimes qualified as *virtual* to distinguish them from their physical counterparts, e.g.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] *virtual* buttons that can be clicked with a pointer, vs. physical buttons that can be pressed with a finger (such as those on a computer mouse).
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] A related (but different) concept is the desktop widget, a small specialized GUI application that provides some visual information and/or easy access to frequently used functions such as clocks, calendars, news aggregators, calculators and desktop notes.
[src:x11-windowing/graphical-widget] These kinds of widgets are hosted by a widget engine.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] A **window manager** is system software that controls the placement and appearance of windows within a windowing system in a graphical user interface.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Most window managers are designed to help provide a desktop environment.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] They work in conjunction with the underlying graphical system that provides required functionality—support for graphics hardware, pointing devices, and a keyboard—and are often written and created using a widget toolkit.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Few window managers are designed with a clear distinction between the windowing system and the window manager.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Every graphical user interface based on a windows metaphor has some form of window management.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] In practice, the elements of this functionality vary greatly.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Elements usually associated with window managers allow the user to open, close, minimize, maximize, move, resize, and keep track of running windows, including window decorators.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] In 1973, the Xerox Alto became the first computer shipped with a working WIMP GUI.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] It used a stacking window manager that allowed overlapping windows.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] However, this was so far ahead of its time that its design paradigm would not become widely adopted until more than a decade later.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] While it is unclear if Microsoft Windows contains designs copied from Apple's classic Mac OS, it is clear that neither was the first to produce a GUI using stacking windows.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] In the early 1980s, the Xerox Star, successor to the Alto, used tiling for most main application windows, and used overlapping only for dialogue boxes, removing most of the need for stacking.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] The classic Mac OS was one of the earliest commercially successful examples of a GUI that used a sort of stacking window management via QuickDraw.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Its successor, macOS, uses a somewhat more advanced window manager that has supported compositing since Mac OS X 10.0, and was updated in Mac OS X 10.2 to support hardware accelerated compositing via the Quartz Compositor.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] GEM 1.1, from Digital Research, was a operating environment that included a stacking window manager, allowing all windows to overlap.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] GEM is famous for having been included as the main GUI used on the Atari ST, which ran Atari TOS, and was also a popular GUI for MS-DOS prior to the widespread use of Microsoft Windows.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] As a result of a lawsuit by Apple, Digital Research was forced to remove the stacking capabilities in GEM 2.0, making its window manager a tiling window manager.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Additionally, Intuition supported compositing.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] The Amiga windowing system would then use a series of bit blits using the system's hardware blitter to build a composite of these applications' bitmaps, along with buttons and sliders, in display memory, without requiring these applications to redraw any of their bitmaps.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] In 1988, Presentation Manager became the default shell in OS/2, which, in its first version, only used a command line interface (CLI).
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] IBM and Microsoft designed OS/2 as a successor to DOS and Windows for DOS.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] After the success of Windows 3.10, however, Microsoft abandoned the project in favor of Windows.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] After that, the Microsoft project for a future OS/2 version 3 became Windows NT, and IBM made a complete redesign of the shell of OS/2, substituting the Presentation Manager of OS/2 1.x for the object-oriented Workplace Shell that made its debut in OS/2 2.0.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] On systems using the X Window System, there is a clear distinction between the window manager and the windowing system.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Strictly speaking, an X window manager does not directly interact with video hardware, mice, or keyboards – that is the responsibility of the display server.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] A desktop environment typically integrates a default window manager: for instance GNOME 2 uses Metacity, while KDE Plasma Workspaces uses KWin.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] But X Window System's modular design allows the user to switch to a different window manager: for instance Compiz (a 3D compositing manager) may be used if 3D effects are desired, while Sawfish and awesome instead offer exacting window control.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Some components of different window managers can even be mixed and matched; for example, the window decorations from KWin can be used with the desktop and dock components of GNOME.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] X window managers also have the ability to re-parent applications, meaning that, while initially all applications are adopted by the root window (essentially the whole screen), an application started within the root window can be adopted by (i.e., put inside of) another window.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Window managers under the X window system adopt applications from the root window and re-parent them to apply window decorations (for example, adding a title bar).
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Re-parenting can also be used to add the contents of one window to another.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] For example, a flash player application can be re-parented to a browser window, and can appear to the user as supposedly being part of that program.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Re-parenting window managers can therefore arrange one or more programs within the same window, and can easily combine tiling and stacking in various ways.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Microsoft Windows has provided an integrated stacking window manager since Windows 2.0; Windows Vista introduced the compositing Desktop Window Manager (dwm.exe) as an optional hardware-accelerated alternative.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] In Windows, since GDI is part of the kernel, the role of the window manager is tightly coupled with the kernel's graphical subsystems and is largely non-replaceable, although third-party utilities can be used to simulate a tiling window manager on top of such systems.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Window management on Windows can also be enhanced with third-party tools such as WindowBlinds, Resource Hacker, and Smartpanels.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Since Windows 8, the Direct3D-based Desktop Window Manager can no longer be disabled.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] It can only be restarted with the hotkey combination Ctrl+Shift+Win+B.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] A complete X Windows Server, allowing the use of window managers ported from the unixoid world can also be provided for Microsoft Windows through Cygwin/X even in *multiwindow* mode (and by other X Window System implementations).
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Thereby, it is easily possible to e.g. have X Window System client programs running either in the same Cygwin environment on the same machine, or on a Linux, BSD Unix etc. system via the network, and only their GUI being displayed and usable on top of the Microsoft Windows environment.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Note that Microsoft and X Window System use different terms to describe similar concepts.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] For example, there is rarely any mention of the term *window manager* by Microsoft because it is integrated and non-replaceable, and distinct from the *shell*.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] The Windows Shell is analogous to the desktop environment concept in other graphical user interface systems.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Since 2021 ChromeOS is shipped with its own window manager called Ash.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] In the past one could run it by using `google-chrome --open-ash` on any compatible systems.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Window managers are often divided into three or more classes, which describe how windows are drawn and updated.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Compositing window managers let all windows be created and drawn separately and then put together and displayed in various 2D and 3D environments.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] The most advanced compositing window managers allow for a great deal of variety in interface look and feel, and for the presence of advanced 2D and 3D visual effects.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] All window managers that have overlapping windows and are not compositing window managers are stacking window managers, although it is possible that not all use the same methods.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Stacking window managers allow windows to overlap by drawing background windows first, which is referred to as the painter's algorithm.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Changes sometimes require that all windows be re-stacked or repainted, which usually involves redrawing every window.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] However, to bring a background window to the front usually only requires that one window be redrawn, since background windows may have bits of other windows painted over them, effectively erasing the areas that are covered.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Tiling window managers paint all windows on-screen by placing them side by side or above and below each other, so that no window ever covers another.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Microsoft Windows 1.0 used tiling, and a variety of tiling window managers for X are available, such as i3, awesome, and dwm.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Dynamic window managers can dynamically switch between tiling or floating window layout.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] A variety of dynamic window managers for X are available.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] is moved away from the edge of the screen.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] that appears when an alternative click event is applied to a desktop component.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] is a facility some window managers provide.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] It allows an application not in focus to suddenly gain focus and steal user input intended for the previously focused application.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] facility that lets user join application window frames together.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] a component of some window managers that provides the facility to launch programs using a menu.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] , rather than a horizontal or vertical bar.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] affects the input focus within the window manager.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] is a facility that centres the pointer on the current application as it is made active.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] that access specific programs or facilities.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] facility that groups applications together in common frames.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] A start button is a desktop widget that provides a menu of programs that can be launched.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] to indicate status information and notifications such as arrival of a new mail message.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] component some window managers provide at the top of each window.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] is typically used to display the name of the application, or the name of the open document, and may provide title bar buttons for minimizing, maximizing, closing or rolling up of application windows.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] of some window managers, and provide the facility to minimize, maximize, rollup or close application windows.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] An active window is the currently focused window in the current window manager.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Different window managers indicate the currently-active window in different ways and allow the user to switch between windows in different ways.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] For example, in Microsoft Windows, if both Notepad and Microsoft Paint are open, clicking in the Notepad window will cause that window to become active.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] In Windows, the active window is indicated by having a different colored title bar.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Clicking is not the only way of selecting an active window, however: some window managers (such as FVWM) make the window under the mouse pointer active—simply moving the mouse is sufficient to switch windows; a click is not needed.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Window managers often provide a way to select the active window using the keyboard as an alternative to the mouse.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] One typical key combination is Alt+Tab, used by Windows and KDE (by default, though this is user-configurable); another is apple key-tilde, used by Macintosh.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Pressing the appropriate key combination typically cycles through all visible windows in some order, though other actions are possible.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Many, though not all, window managers provide a region of the screen containing some kind of visual control (often a button) for each window on the screen.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Each button typically contains the title of the window and may also contain an icon.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] This area of the screen generally provides some kind of visual indication of which window is active—for example, the active window's button may appear “pushed in”.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] It is also usually possible to switch the active window by clicking on the appropriate button.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] In Microsoft Windows, this area of the screen is called the *taskbar*; in Apple Macintosh systems this area of the screen is called the dock.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] The active window may not always lie in front of all other windows on the screen.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] The active window is simply the window to which keys typed on the keyboard are sent; it may be visually obscured by other windows.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] This is especially true in window managers which do not require a click to change active windows: FVWM, for example, makes active the window under the mouse cursor but does not change its Z-order (the order in which windows appear, measured from background to foreground).
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] Instead, it is necessary to click on the border of the window to bring it to the foreground.
[src:x11-windowing/window-manager] There are also situations in click-to-focus window managers such as Microsoft Windows where the active window may be obscured; however, this is much less common.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Implementations of the client-side X Window System protocol exist in the form of *X11 libraries*, which serve as helpful APIs for communicating with the X server.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Two such major X libraries exist for X11.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The first of these libraries was Xlib, the original C language X11 API, but another C language X library, XCB, was created later in 2001.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Other smaller X libraries exist, both as interfaces for Xlib and XCB in other languages, and as smaller standalone X libraries.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The services with which the X.Org Foundation supports X Server include the packaging of the releases; certification (for a fee); evaluation of improvements to the code; developing the web site, and handling the distribution of monetary donations.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The releases are coded, documented, and packaged by global developers.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The X.Org Server implements the server side of the X Window System core protocol version 11 (X11) and extensions to it, e.g.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Version 1.16.0 integrates support for systemd-based launching and management which improved boot performance and reliability.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The Device Independent X (DIX) is the part of the X.Org Server that interacts with clients and implements software rendering.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The main loop and the event delivery are part of the DIX.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] An X server has a tremendous amount of functionality that must be implemented to support the X core protocol.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] This includes code tables, glyph rasterization and caching, XLFDs, and the core rendering API which draws graphics primitives.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The Device Dependent X (DDX) is the part of the x-server that interacts with the hardware.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] In the X.Org Server source code, each directory under "hw" corresponds to one DDX.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Hardware comprises graphics cards as well as mouse and keyboards.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Each driver is hardware specific and implemented as a separate loadable module.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] For historical reasons the X.Org Server still contains graphics device drivers supporting some form of 2D rendering acceleration.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] In the past, mode-setting was done by an X-server graphics device driver specific to some video controller hardware (*e.g.*, a GPU).
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] To this mode-setting functionality, additional support for 2D acceleration was added when such became available with various GPUs.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The mode-setting functionality was moved into the DRM and is being exposed through a DRM mode-setting interface, the new approach being called "kernel mode-setting" (KMS).
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] But the 2D rendering acceleration remained.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] In Debian the 2D graphics drivers for the X.Org Server are packaged individually and called *xserver-xorg-video-**.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] After installation the 2D graphics driver-file is found under `/usr/lib/xorg/modules/drivers/`.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The package xserver-xorg-video-nouveau installs `nouveau_drv.so` with a size of 215 KiB, the proprietary Nvidia GeForce driver installs an 8 MiB-sized file called `nvidia_drv.so` and Radeon Software installs `fglrx_drv.so` with a size of about 25MiB.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The available free and open-source graphics device drivers are being developed inside of the Mesa 3D-project.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] While these can be recompiled as required, the development of the proprietary DDX 2D graphics drivers is greatly eased when the X.Org Server keeps a stable API/ABI across multiple of its versions.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] With version 1.17 a generic method for mode-setting was mainlined.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The `xf86-video-modesetting` package, the Debian-package being called `xserver-xorg-video-modesetting`, was retired, and the generic modesetting DDX it contained was moved into the server package to become the KMS-enabled default DDX, supporting the vast majority of AMD, Intel and NVidia GPUs.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] On April 7, 2016, AMD employee Michel Dänzer released `xf86-video-ati` version 7.7.0 and `xf86-video-amdgpu` version 1.1.0, the latter including support for their Polaris microarchitecture.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] There are (at least) XAA (XFree86 Acceleration Architecture), EXA, UXA and SNA.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] In the X Window System, **XFree86 Acceleration Architecture** (**XAA**) is a driver architecture to make a video card's 2D hardware acceleration available to the X server.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] It was written by Harm Hanemaayer in 1996 and first released in XFree86 version 3.3.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] It was completely rewritten for XFree86 4.0.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] It was removed again from X.Org Server 1.13.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Most drivers implement acceleration using the XAA module.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] XAA is on by default, though acceleration of individual functions can be switched off as needed in the server configuration file (`XF86Config` or `xorg.conf`).
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The driver for the ARK chipset was the original development platform for XAA.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] In X.Org Server release 6.9/7.0, EXA was released as a replacement for XAA, as XAA supplies almost no speed advantage for current video cards.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] EXA is regarded as an intermediate step to converting the entire X server to using OpenGL.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Glamor is a generic, hardware independent, 2D acceleration driver for the X server that translates the X render primitives into OpenGL operations, taking advantage of any existing 3D OpenGL drivers.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] In this way, it is functionally similar to Quartz Extreme and QuartzGL (2D performance acceleration) for Apple Quartz Compositor.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The ultimate goal of GLAMOR is to obsolete and replace all the DDX 2D graphics device drivers and acceleration architectures, thereby avoiding the need to write X 2D specific drivers for every supported graphic chipset.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Glamor requires a 3D driver with support for shaders.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Glamor performance tuning was accepted for Google Summer of Code 2014.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Glamor supports Xephyr and DRI3, and can boost some operations by 700–800%.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Since its mainlining into version 1.16 of the X.Org Server, development on Glamor was continued and patches for the 1.17 release were published.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] There is a distinct and special DDX for instances of the X.Org Server which run on a guest system inside of a virtualized environment: xf86-video-qxl, a driver for the "QXL video device".
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] SPICE makes use of this driver though it works without it as well.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] In the Debian repositories it is called xserver-xorg-video-qxl.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Under Debian, drivers related to input are found under `/usr/lib/xorg/modules/input/`.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] `evdev_drv.so`, `mouse_drv.so`, `synaptics_drv.so` or `wacom_drv.so`.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] With version 1.16, the X.Org Server obtained support for the libinput library in form of a wrapper called `xf86-input-libinput`.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] At the XDC 2015 in Toronto, libratbag was introduced as a generic library to support configurable mice.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] `xserver-xorg-input-joystick` is the input module for the X.Org server to handle classic joysticks and gamepads, which is not meant for playing games under X, but to control the cursor with a joystick or gamepad.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] and were mainlined in version 1.16 of the X.Org Server in 2014.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] , it calls upon XWayland to service the request.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Xspice is a device driver for the X.Org Server.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Since version 1.16.0, Xephyr serves as the primary development environment for the new 2D acceleration subsystem (Glamor), permitting rapid development and testing on a single machine.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] RandR is responsible for setting the screen refresh rate.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] It allows for the control of multiple monitors.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The X.Org Server, and any x-client, each run as distinct processes.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] On Unix/Linux, a process knows nothing about any other processes.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] For it to communicate with another process, it is completely and utterly reliant on the kernel to moderate the communication via available inter-process communication (IPC) mechanisms.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Unix domain sockets are used to communicate with processes running on the same machine.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Special socket function calls are part of the System Call Interface.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Although Internet domain sockets can be used locally, Unix domain sockets are more efficient, since they do not have the protocol overhead (checksums, byte orders, etc.).
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Sockets are the most common interprocess communication (IPC) method between the processes of the X server and its various X clients.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] It provides the Application Programming Interface (API) for communication in the TCP/IP domain and also locally only in the UNIX domain.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] There are several other APIs described in the X Transport Interface, for instance TLI (Transport Layer Interface).
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Other options for IPC between for the X client-server, require X Window system extensions, for instance the MIT Shared Memory Extension (MIT-SHM).
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Multi-seat refers to an assembly of a single computer with multiple "seats", allowing multiple users to sit down at the computer, log in, and use the computer at the same time independently.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The computer has multiple keyboards, mice, and monitors attached to it, each "seat" having one keyboard, one mouse and one monitor assigned to it.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] A "seat" consists of all hardware devices assigned to a specific workplace.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] It consists of at least one graphics device (graphics card or just an output and the attached monitor) and a keyboard and a mouse.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] It can also include video cameras, sound cards and more.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Due to limitation of the VT system in the Linux kernel and of the X core protocol (in particular, how X defines the relation between the root window and an output of the graphics card), multi-seat does not work out-of-the-box for the usual Linux distribution but necessitates a special configuration.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Only the user on the first monitor has the use of vt consoles and can use Ctrl+Alt+Fx to select them.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The other users have a GDM login screen and can use xorg-server normally, but have no vt's.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Even though a single user can utilize multiple monitors connected to the different ports of a single graphics card (cf.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] RandR), the method which is based on multiple instances of the xorg-server seems to require multiple PCI graphics cards.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] It is possible to configure multi-seat employing only one graphics card, but due to limitations of the X protocol this necessitates the usage of X Display Manager Control Protocol XDMCP.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] There is also Xdmx (Distributed Multihead X).
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] allow launching of X applications through X11 forwarding on the condition that it is enabled on both the server and client.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] (10.5) shipped with an XFree86-based server, but 10.5's X server adopted the X.Org codebase.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] to X11 apps, which run in pixel-doubled mode on high-resolution displays.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The modern X.Org Foundation came into being in 2004 when the body that oversaw X standards and published the official reference implementation joined forces with former XFree86 developers.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] X11R6.7.0, the first version of the X.Org Server, was forked from XFree86 4.4 RC2.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The immediate reason for the fork was a disagreement with the new license for the final release version of XFree86 4.4, but several disagreements among the contributors surfaced prior to the split.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Many of the previous XFree86 developers have joined the X.Org Server project.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] In 2005, a great effort was put in the modularization of the X.Org server source code, resulting in a dual release by the end of the year.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The X11R7.0.0 release added a new modular build system based on the GNU Autotools, while X11R6.9.0 kept the old imake build system, both releases sharing the same codebase.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Since then the X11R6.9 branch is maintained frozen and all the ongoing development is done to the modular branch.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] The new build system also brought the use of dlloader standard dynamic linker to load plugins and drivers, deprecating the old own method.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] As a consequence of the modularization, the X11 binaries were moving out of their own `/usr/X11R6` subdirectory tree and into the global `/usr` tree on many Unix systems.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] In June 2006, another effort was done to move the X.Org server source codebase from CVS to git.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] Both efforts had the long-term goal of bringing new developers to the project.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] In the 7.1 release, the KDrive framework (a small implementation of X written by Keith Packard, which was not based on XFree86 that X.Org developers used as a testing ground for new ideas, such as EXA) was integrated into the main codebase of X.Org server.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] In 2008, the new DRI2, based on the kernel mode-setting (KMS) driver, replaced DRI.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] This change also set a major milestone in the X.Org server architecture, as the drivers were moved out from the server and user space (UMS) to the kernel space.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] In 2013, the initial versions of DRI3 and Present extensions were written and coded by Keith Packard to provide a faster and tearing-free 2D rendering.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] By the end of the year the implementation of GLX was rewritten by Adam Jackson at Red Hat.
[src:x11-windowing/x-org-server] In June 2025, a fork of X.Org Server called XLibre was released.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] In computing, the X Window System (commonly: X11, or X) is a network-transparent windowing system for bitmap displays.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] This article details the protocols and technical structure of X11.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] An *X server* program runs on a computer with a graphical display and communicates with various *client programs*.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] In X, the server runs on the user's computer, while the clients may run on remote machines.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] This terminology reverses the common notion of client–server systems, where the *client* normally runs on the user's local computer and the server runs on the remote computer.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The X terminology takes the perspective that the X program is at the centre of all activity, i.e. the X program accepts and responds to requests from applications, and from the user's mouse and keyboard input.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Therefore, applications (on remote computers) are viewed as clients of the X server program.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The communication protocol between server and client runs network-transparently: the client and server may run on the same machine or on different ones, possibly with different architectures and operating systems.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] A client and server can communicate securely over the Internet by tunneling the connection over an encrypted connection.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] X has largely kept to these principles since.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The X.Org Foundation develops the reference implementation with a view to extension and improvement of the implementation, whilst keeping it almost entirely compatible with the original 1987 protocol.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Communication between server and clients is done by exchanging packets over a network channel.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The client establishes the connection, sending the first packet.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The server answers by sending back a packet stating the acceptance or refusal of the connection, or with a request for a further authentication.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] If the connection is accepted, the acceptance packet contains data for the client to use in the subsequent interaction with the server.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] **Reply:** the server responds to a request.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] **Event:** the server sends an event to the client, e.g., keyboard or mouse input, or a window being moved, resized or exposed.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] **Error:** the server sends an error packet if a request is invalid.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Since requests are queued, error packets generated by a request may not be sent immediately.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The X server provides a set of basic services.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The client programs realize more complex functionalities by interacting with the server.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] What other graphical user interfaces usually call a *window* is a *top-level window* in the X Window System.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The term *window* is also used for windows that lie within another window, that is, the *subwindows* of a *parent window*.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Graphical elements such as buttons, menus, icons, etc. are all realized using windows.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] A window can only be created as a subwindow of a parent window.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] This causes the windows to be arranged hierarchically in a tree.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The X server automatically creates the root of the tree, called the root window.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The top-level windows are exactly the direct subwindows of the root window.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Visibly, the root window is as large as the screen, and lies behind all other windows.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The X server stores all data about windows, fonts, etc.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The client knows identifiers of these objects – integers it can use as names for them when interacting with the server.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] For example, if a client wishes a window to be created, it requests the server to create one and (in case of success) gets in return an identifier the server associated with the newly created window.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The identifier can be later used by the client to request, for example, a string to be drawn in the window.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Identifiers are unique to the server, not only to the client; for example, no two windows have the same identifier, even if created by two different clients.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] A client can access any object given its identifier, even if another client created the object.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Every window has a predefined set of attributes and a set of properties, all stored in the X server and accessible to the clients via appropriate requests.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Attributes are data about the window, such as its size, position, background color, etc.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Properties are pieces of data that are attached to a window.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Unlike attributes, properties have no meaning at the level of the X core protocol.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] A client can store arbitrary data in a property of a window.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] A property is characterized by a name, a type, and a value.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Properties resemble variables in imperative programming languages, in that the application can create a new property with a given name and of a given type and store a value in it.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Properties are associated to windows: two properties with the same name can exist on two different windows while having different types and values.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Properties are mostly used for inter-client communication.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] For example, the property named `WM_NAME` stores the name for the window; window managers typically read this property and display the name of the window at the top of it.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The `xprop` program can display the properties of a window.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] In particular, `xprop -root` shows the properties of the root window, which include the X resources (parameters of programs).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Events are packets sent by the server to the client to communicate that something has happened which may interest the client.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] A client can request the server to send an event to another client; this is used for communication between clients.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] For example, when a client requests the text that is currently selected, an event is sent to the client that is currently handling the window that holds the selection.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The content of a window may be "destroyed" in some conditions (for example, if the window is covered).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Whenever an area of destroyed content is made visible, the server generates an `Expose` event to notify the client that a part of the window has to be drawn.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Other events can serve to notify clients of keyboard or mouse input, of the creation of new windows, etc.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Some kinds of events are always sent to a client, but most kinds of event are sent only if the client previously stated an interest in them, because clients may only be interested in some kind of events.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] For example, a client may be interested in keyboard-related event but not in mouse-related events.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The way the X Window System handles colors can sometimes confuse users, and historically several different modes have been supported.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Most modern applications use full color (24-bit color, 8 bits for each of red, green and blue), but old or specialist applications may require a different color mode.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Many commercial specialist applications use PseudoColor.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The X11 protocol actually uses a single 32-bit unsigned integer - called a *pixelvalue* - for representing a single color in most graphic operations.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] When transferring the intensity of primary colors, a 16 bit integer is used for each color component.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The following representations of colors exist; not all of them may be supported on a specific device.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Most client programs communicate with the server via the Xlib client library.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Beside Xlib, the XCB library operates more closely to X protocol.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] In particular, most clients use libraries such as Xaw, Motif, GTK+, or Qt which in turn use Xlib for interacting with the server.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Qt switched from Xlib to XCB with the 5.0 release, but client programs were almost entirely unaffected by this change.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The X core protocol provides mechanisms for communication between clients: window properties and events, in particular the client-to-client message events.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] However, it does not specify any protocol for such interactions.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Instead, a separate set of inter-client communication conventions governs these protocols.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The Inter-Client Communication Conventions Manual specifies the protocol for the exchange of data via selections and the interaction of applications with the window manager.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Some have considered this specification difficult and confusing; consistency of application look and feel and communication is typically addressed by programming to a given desktop environment.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The Inter-Client Exchange protocol (ICE) specifies a framework for building protocols for interaction between clients, so that programmers can build a specific protocol on top of it.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The mechanisms of selections, cut buffers, and drag-and-drop in the X Window System allow a user to transfer data from one window to another.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Selections and cut buffer are used (typically) when a user selects text or some other data in a window and pastes in a different window.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Drag-and-drop is used when a user selects something in a window, then clicks on the selection and drags it into another window.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Since two different applications may handle the two windows, data transfer requires different clients connected with the same X server to interact.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The X core protocol includes some types of requests and events that are specific to selection exchange, but the transfer is mainly done using the general client-to-client event sending and window properties, which are not specific to selection transfer.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Users can transfer data of different types between clients: it is usually text, but can also be a pixmap, a number, a list of objects, etc.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Selections and drag-and-drop are active mechanisms: after the user selects data in a window, the client handling the window must actively support a protocol for transferring that data to the application requesting it.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Cut buffers, by contrast, provide a passive mechanism: when the user selects some text, its content is transferred to a cut buffer, where it remains even if the application handling the window terminates and the window is destroyed.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] A window manager is a program that controls the general appearance of windows and other graphical elements of the graphical user interface.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Differences in the look of X Window System in different installations stem mainly from the use of different window managers or from different configurations of the window manager.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The window manager takes care of deciding the position of windows, placing the decorative border around them, handling icons, handling mouse clicks outside windows (on the “background”), handling certain keystrokes, etc.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] From the point of view of the X server, the window manager operates as a client just like any other client.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] 2. an application can request changing the parent of a window.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The window manager uses the first request to intercept any request for mapping top-level windows (children of the root window).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Whenever another application requests the mapping of a top-level window, the server does not do it but sends an event to the window manager instead.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Most window managers reparent the window: they create a larger top-level window (called the frame window) and reparent the original window as a child of it.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Graphically, this corresponds to placing the original window inside the frame window.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The space of the frame window that is not taken by the original window is used for the decorative frame around the window (the “border” and the “title bar”).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The window manager manages mouse clicks in the frame window.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] This allows, for example, a user to move or resize the window by clicking and dragging on the border or on the title bar.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The window manager also handles icons and related visual elements of the graphical user interface.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Icons do not exist at the level of the X core protocol.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] They are implemented by the window manager.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] For example, whenever a window has to be “iconified”, the FVWM window manager unmaps the window, and creates a window for the icon name and possibly another window for the icon image.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The meaning and handling of icons is therefore completely decided by the window manager: some window managers such as wm2 do not implement icons at all.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Roughly, the state of a session is the “state of the desktop” at a given time: a set of windows with their current content.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] More precisely, it is the set of applications managing these windows and the information that allow these applications to restore the condition of their managed windows if required.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] A program known as the X session manager saves and restores the state of sessions.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Most recognizably, using a session manager permits a user to log out from an interactive session but to find exactly the same windows in the same state when logging in again.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] For this to work, the session manager program stores the names of the running applications at logout and starts them again at login.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] In order for the state of the applications to be restored as well (which is needed to restore the content of windows), the applications must be able to save their state of execution upon request from the session manager and load it back when they start again.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The X Window System includes a default session manager called `xsm`.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Developers have written other session managers for specific desktop systems.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Major examples include `ksmserver`, `xfce4-session`, and `gnome-session` for KDE, Xfce, and GNOME respectively.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The program known as the X display manager shows the graphical login prompt in the X Window System.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] More generally, a display manager runs one or more X servers on the local computer or accepts incoming connections from X servers running on remote computers.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The local servers are started by the display manager, which then connects to them to present the user the login screen.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The remote servers are started independently from the display manager and connect to it.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] The X Window System ships with XDM as the basic supplied display manager.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Other display managers include GDM (GNOME), KDM/SDDM (KDE), WDM (using the WINGs widget set used in Window Maker) and entrance (using the architecture used in Enlightenment v.17).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Early widget toolkits for X included Xaw (the Athena Widget Set, 1983), OLIT (OPEN LOOK Intrinsics Toolkit, 1988), XView (1988), Motif (1980s) and Tk.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] OLIT and XView function as the base toolkits for Sun's legacy OpenWindows desktop environment.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Motif provides the base toolkit for the Common Desktop Environment (CDE), the desktop environment used on commercial Unix systems such as Solaris, AIX and HP-UX.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Scheifler and Gettys designed the X server to be simple but extensible.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] As such, much functionality now resides in extensions to the protocol.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] At the protocol level, every extension can be assigned new request/event/error packet types.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Extension features are accessed by client applications through extension libraries.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] Adding extensions to current X server implementations is reportedly difficult due to a lack of modularity in the server design.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system-protocols-and-architecture] It is a long-term goal of the XCB project to automate generating both the client and server sides of extensions from XML protocol descriptions.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The **X Window System** (**X11**, or simply **X**) is a windowing system for bitmap displays, common on Unix-like operating systems.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X originated as part of Project Athena at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) in 1984.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The X protocol has been at version 11 (hence "X11") since September 1987.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The X.Org Foundation leads the X project, with the current reference implementation, X.Org Server, available as free and open-source software under the MIT License and similar permissive licenses.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X is an architecture-independent system for remote graphical user interfaces and input device capabilities.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Each person using a networked terminal has the ability to interact with the display with any type of user input device.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The standard distribution delivers a standard toolkit and protocol stack for building graphical user interfaces on most Unix-like operating systems and OpenVMS, and has been ported to many other contemporary general purpose operating systems.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X provides the basic framework, or primitives, for building such GUI environments: drawing and moving windows on the display and interacting with a mouse, keyboard or touchscreen.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X does not mandate the user interface; individual client programs handle this.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Programs may use X's graphical abilities with no user interface.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] As such, the visual styling of X-based environments varies greatly; different programs may present radically different interfaces.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Unlike most earlier display protocols, X was specifically designed to be used over network connections rather than on an integral or attached display device.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X features network transparency, which means an X program running on a computer somewhere on a network (such as the Internet) can display its user interface on an X server running on some other computer on the network.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The fact that the term "server" is applied to the software in front of the user is often surprising to users accustomed to their programs being clients to services on remote computers.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X's network protocol is based on X command primitives.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] This approach allows both 2D and (through extensions like GLX) 3D operations by an X client application which might be running on a different computer to still be fully accelerated on the X server's display.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] For example, in classic OpenGL (before version 3.0), display lists containing large numbers of objects could be constructed and stored entirely in the X server by a remote X client program, and each then rendered by sending a single glCallList(which) across the network.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X provides no native support for audio; several projects exist to fill this niche, some also providing transparent network support.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X uses a client–server model: an X server communicates with various *client* programs.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The server accepts requests for graphical output (windows) and sends back user input (from keyboard, mouse, or touchscreen).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] This client–server terminology – the user's terminal being the server and the applications being the clients – often confuses new X users, because the terms appear reversed.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] But X takes the perspective of the application, rather than that of the end-user: X provides display and I/O services to applications, so it is a server; applications use these services, thus they are clients.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The communication protocol between server and client operates network-transparently: the client and server may run on the same machine or on different ones, possibly with different architectures and operating systems.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] A client and server can even communicate securely over the Internet by tunneling the connection over an encrypted network session.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] An X client itself may emulate an X server by providing display services to other clients.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Open-source clients such as Xnest and Xephyr support such X nesting.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The remote X client application will then make a connection to the user's local X server, providing display and input to the user.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Alternatively, the local machine may run a small program that connects to the remote machine and starts the client application.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X primarily defines protocol and graphics primitives – it deliberately contains no specification for application user-interface design, such as button, menu, or window title-bar styles.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Instead, application software – such as window managers, GUI widget toolkits and desktop environments, or application-specific graphical user interfaces – define and provide such details.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] As a result, there is no *typical* X interface and several different desktop environments have become popular among users.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] A window manager controls the placement and appearance of application windows.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] This may result in desktop interfaces reminiscent of those of Microsoft Windows or of the Apple Macintosh (examples include GNOME 2, KDE Plasma, Xfce) or have radically different controls (such as a tiling window manager, like wmii or Ratpoison).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Some interfaces such as Sugar or ChromeOS eschew the desktop metaphor altogether, simplifying their interfaces for specialized applications.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Many users use X with a desktop environment, which, aside from the window manager, includes various applications using a consistent user interface.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Popular desktop environments include GNOME, KDE Plasma and Xfce.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The UNIX 98 standard environment is the Common Desktop Environment (CDE).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The freedesktop.org initiative addresses interoperability between desktops and the components needed for a competitive X desktop.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The X.Org implementation is the canonical implementation of X.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Owing to liberal licensing, a number of variations, both free and open-source (FOSS) and proprietary, have appeared.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Commercial Unix vendors have tended to take the reference implementation and adapt it for their hardware, usually customizing it and adding proprietary extensions.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Until 2004, XFree86 provided the most common X variant on free Unix-like systems.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] XFree86 started as a port of X to 386-compatible PCs and, by the end of the 1990s, had become the greatest source of technical innovation in X and the *de facto* standard of X development.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Since 2004, however, the X.Org Server, a fork of XFree86, has become predominant.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] While it is common to associate X with Unix, X servers also exist natively within other graphical environments.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] VMS Software Inc.'s OpenVMS operating system includes a version of X with Common Desktop Environment (CDE), known as DECwindows, as its standard desktop environment.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Apple originally ported X to macOS in the form of X11.app, but that has been deprecated in favor of the XQuartz implementation.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Third-party servers under Apple's older operating systems in the 1990s, System 7, and Mac OS 8 and 9, included Apple's MacX and White Pine Software's eXodus.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Microsoft Windows is not shipped with support for X, but many third-party implementations exist, as free and open source software such as Cygwin/X, and proprietary products such as Exceed, MKS X/Server, Reflection X, X-Win32 and Xming.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] There are also Java implementations of X servers.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] WeirdX runs on any platform supporting Swing 1.1, and will run as an applet within most browsers.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The Android X Server is an open source Java implementation that runs on Android devices.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] An *X terminal* is a thin client that only runs an X server.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] This architecture became popular for building inexpensive terminal parks for many users to simultaneously use the same large computer server to execute application programs as clients of each user's X terminal.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] This use is very much aligned with the original intention of the MIT project.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X terminals explore the network (the local broadcast domain) using the X Display Manager Control Protocol to generate a list of available hosts that are allowed as clients.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] One of the client hosts should run an X display manager.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] A limitation of X terminals and most thin clients is that they are not capable of any input or output other than the keyboard, mouse, and display.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] All relevant data is assumed to exist solely on the remote server, and the X terminal user has no methods available to save or load data from a local peripheral device.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Dedicated (hardware) X terminals have fallen out of use; a PC or modern thin client with an X server typically provides the same functionality at the same, or lower, cost.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The lack of design guidelines in X has resulted in several vastly different interfaces, and in applications that have not always worked well together.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The Inter-Client Communication Conventions Manual (ICCCM), a specification for client interoperability, has a reputation for being difficult to implement correctly.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Further standards efforts such as Motif and CDE did not alleviate problems.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] This has frustrated users and programmers.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Graphics programmers now generally address consistency of application look and feel and communication by coding to a specific desktop environment or to a specific widget toolkit, which also avoids having to deal directly with the ICCCM.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X also lacks native support for user-defined stored procedures on the X server, in the manner of NeWS – there is no Turing-complete scripting facility.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Various desktop environments may thus offer their own (usually mutually incompatible) facilities.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Systems built upon X may have accessibility issues that make utilization of a computer difficult for disabled users, including right click, double click, middle click, mouse-over, and focus stealing.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Some X11 clients deal with accessibility issues better than others, so persons with accessibility problems are not locked out of using X11.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] However, there is no accessibility standard or accessibility guidelines for X11.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Within the X11 standards process there is no working group on accessibility; however, accessibility needs are being addressed by software projects to provide these features on top of X.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The Orca project adds accessibility support to the X Window System, including implementing an API (AT-SPI).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] This is coupled with GNOME's ATK to allow for accessibility features to be implemented in X programs using the GNOME/GTK APIs.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] KDE provides a different set of accessibility software, including a text-to-speech converter and a screen magnifier.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The other major desktops (LXDE, Xfce and Enlightenment) attempt to be compatible with ATK.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] An X client cannot generally be detached from one server and reattached to another unless its code specifically provides for it (Emacs is one of the few common programs with this ability).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] As such, moving an entire session from one X server to another is generally not possible.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] However, approaches like Virtual Network Computing (VNC), NX and Xpra allow a virtual session to be reached from different X servers (in a manner similar to GNU Screen in relation to terminals), and other applications and toolkits provide related facilities.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Workarounds like x11vnc (*VNC :0 viewers*), Xpra's shadow mode and NX's nxagent shadow mode also exist to make the current X-server screen available.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] This ability allows the user interface (mouse, keyboard, monitor) of a running application to be switched from one location to another without stopping and restarting the application.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Network traffic between an X server and remote X clients is not encrypted by default.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] An attacker with a packet sniffer can intercept it, making it possible to view anything displayed to or sent from the user's screen.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The most common way to encrypt X traffic is to establish a Secure Shell (SSH) tunnel for communication.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Like all thin clients, when using X across a network, bandwidth limitations can impede the use of bitmap-intensive applications that require rapidly updating large portions of the screen with low latency, such as 3D animation or photo editing.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Even a relatively small *uncompressed* 640×480×24 bit 30 fps video stream (~211 Mbit/s) can easily outstrip the bandwidth of a 100 Mbit/s network for a single client.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] In contrast, modern versions of X generally have extensions such as Mesa allowing local display of a local program's graphics to be optimized to bypass the network model and directly control the video card, for use with full-screen video, rendered 3D applications, and other such applications.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X's design requires the clients and server to operate separately, and device independence and the separation of client and server incur overhead.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Most of the overhead comes from network round-trip delay time between client and server (latency) rather than from the protocol itself: the best solutions to performance issues depend on efficient application design.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] A common criticism of X is that its network features result in excessive complexity and decreased performance if only used locally.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Modern X implementations use Unix domain sockets for efficient connections on the same host.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Additionally shared memory (via the MIT-SHM extension) can be employed for faster client–server communication.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] However, the programmer must still explicitly activate and use the shared memory extension.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] It is also necessary to provide fallback paths in order to stay compatible with older implementations, and in order to communicate with non-local X servers.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X's design lacks sandboxing, so any application can access and manipulate; keyboard, mouse, display and clipboard content.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Poorly configured systems may run X11 as root, allowing privilege escalation; in the past this was exploited by unprivileged apps to gain privilege.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Some people have attempted writing alternatives to and replacements for X.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Historical alternatives include Sun's NeWS and NeXT's Display PostScript, both PostScript-based systems supporting user-definable display-side procedures, which X lacked.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Several bitmap display systems preceded X.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] From Xerox came the Alto (1973) and the Star (1981).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] From Apollo Computer came Display Manager (1981).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] From Apple came the Lisa (1983) and the Macintosh (1984).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The Unix world had the Andrew Project (1982) and Rob Pike's Blit terminal (1982).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Carnegie Mellon University produced a remote-access application called Alto Terminal, that displayed overlapping windows on the Xerox Alto, and made remote hosts (typically DEC VAX systems running Unix) responsible for handling window-exposure events and refreshing window contents as necessary.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X derives its name as a successor to a pre-1983 window system called W (the letter preceding X in the English alphabet).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] W used a network protocol supporting terminal and graphics windows, the server maintaining display lists.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The original idea of X emerged at MIT in 1984 as a collaboration between Jim Gettys (of Project Athena) and Bob Scheifler (of the MIT Laboratory for Computer Science).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Scheifler needed a usable display environment for debugging the Argus system.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The project solved this by creating a protocol that could both run local applications and call on remote resources.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] In mid-1983 an initial port of W to Unix ran at one-fifth of its speed under V; in May 1984, Scheifler replaced the synchronous protocol of W with an asynchronous protocol and the display lists with immediate mode graphics to make X version 1.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X became the first windowing system environment to offer true hardware independence and vendor independence.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Scheifler, Gettys and Ron Newman set to work and X progressed rapidly.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] They released Version 6 in January 1985.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] DEC, then preparing to release its first Ultrix workstation, judged X the only windowing system likely to become available in time.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] DEC engineers ported X6 to DEC's QVSS display on MicroVAX.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] In the second quarter of 1985, X acquired color support to function in the DEC VAXstation-II/GPX, forming what became version 9.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] A group at Brown University ported version 9 to the IBM RT PC, but problems with reading unaligned data on the RT forced an incompatible protocol change, leading to version 10 in late 1985.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] By 1986, outside organizations had begun asking for X.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X10R2 was released in January 1986, then X10R3 in February 1986.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Although MIT had licensed X6 to some outside groups for a fee, it decided at this time to license X10R3 and future versions under what became known as the MIT License, intending to popularize X further and, in return, hoping that many more applications would become available.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X10R3 became the first version to achieve wide deployment, with both DEC and Hewlett-Packard releasing products based on it.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Other groups ported X10 to Apollo and to Sun workstations and even to the IBM PC/AT.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Demonstrations of the first commercial application for X (a mechanical computer-aided engineering system from Cognition Inc. that ran on VAXes and remotely displayed on PCs running an X server ported by Jim Fulton and Jan Hardenbergh) took place at the Autofact trade show at that time.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The last version of X10, X10R4, appeared in December 1986.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Attempts were made to enable X servers as real-time collaboration devices, much as Virtual Network Computing (VNC) would later allow a desktop to be shared.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Although X10 offered interesting and powerful functionality, it had become obvious that the X protocol could use a more hardware-neutral redesign before it became too widely deployed, but MIT alone would not have the resources available for such a complete redesign.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] As it happened, DEC's Western Software Laboratory found itself between projects with an experienced team.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Smokey Wallace of DEC WSL and Jim Gettys proposed that DEC WSL build X11 and make it freely available under the same terms as X9 and X10.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] This process started in May 1986, with the protocol finalized in August.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Alpha testing of the software started in February 1987, beta-testing in May; the release of X11 finally occurred on 15 September 1987.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The X11 protocol design, led by Scheifler, was extensively discussed on open mailing lists on the nascent Internet that were bridged to USENET newsgroups.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Gettys moved to California to help lead the X11 development work at WSL from DEC's Systems Research Center, where Phil Karlton and Susan Angebrandt led the X11 sample server design and implementation.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X therefore represents one of the first very large-scale distributed free and open source software projects.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] By the late 1980s X was "Athena's most important single achievement to date," as Simson Garfinkel wrote in 1989.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] DEC reportedly believed that its development alone had made the company's donation to MIT worthwhile.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Gettys joined the design team for the VAXstation 2000 to ensure that X, which DEC called DECwindows, would run on it, and the company assigned 1,200 employees to port X to both Ultrix and VMS.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] By 1990 IBM and Motorola announced their own X terminals.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Bill Joy of Sun Microsystems, which made diskless workstations competing with X terminals, argued that X was technically flawed and could overwhelm networks.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] In 1987, with the success of X11 becoming apparent, MIT wished to relinquish the stewardship of X, but at a June 1987 meeting with nine vendors, the vendors told MIT that they believed in the need for a neutral party to keep X from fragmenting in the marketplace.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] In January 1988, the *MIT X Consortium* formed as a non-profit vendor group, with Scheifler as director, to direct the future development of X in a neutral atmosphere inclusive of commercial and educational interests.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Jim Fulton joined in January 1988 and Keith Packard in March 1988 as senior developers, with Jim focusing on Xlib, fonts, window managers, and utilities; and Keith re-implementing the server.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Peterson, and Stephen Gildea joined later that year, focusing on toolkits and widget sets, working closely with Ralph Swick of MIT Project Athena.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The MIT X Consortium produced several significant revisions to X11, the first (Release 2 – X11R2) in February 1988.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Jay Hersh joined the staff in January 1991 to work on the PEX and X113D functionality.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] He was followed soon after by Ralph Mor (who also worked on PEX) and Dave Sternlicht.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] In 1993, as the MIT X Consortium prepared to depart from MIT, the staff were joined by R.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Gary Cutbill, Kaleb Keithley, and David Wiggins.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] (a non-profit corporation) formed as the successor to the MIT X Consortium.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] In 1995 it took on the development of the Motif toolkit and of the Common Desktop Environment for Unix systems.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The X Consortium dissolved at the end of 1996, producing a final revision, X11R6.3, and a legacy of increasing commercial influence in the development.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] In January 1997, the X Consortium passed stewardship of X to The Open Group, a vendor group formed in early 1996 by the merger of the Open Software Foundation and X/Open.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The Open Group released X11R6.4 in early 1998.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Controversially, X11R6.4 departed from the traditional liberal licensing terms, as the Open Group sought to assure funding for the development of X, and specifically cited XFree86 as not significantly contributing to X.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The new terms would have made X no longer free software: zero-cost for noncommercial use, but a fee otherwise.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] After XFree86 seemed poised to fork, the Open Group relicensed X11R6.4 under the traditional license in September 1998.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The Open Group's last release came as X11R6.4 patch 3.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] XFree86 originated in 1992 from the X386 server for IBM PC compatibles included with X11R5 in 1991, written by Thomas Roell and Mark W.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Snitily and donated to the MIT X Consortium by Snitily Graphics Consulting Services (SGCS).
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] XFree86 evolved over time from just one port of X to the leading and most popular implementation and the *de facto* standard of X's development.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] In May 1999, The Open Group formed X.Org.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X.Org supervised the release of versions X11R6.5.1 onward.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X development at this time had become moribund; most technical innovation since the X Consortium had dissolved had taken place in the XFree86 project.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] In 1999, the XFree86 team joined X.Org as an honorary (non-paying) member, encouraged by various hardware companies interested in using XFree86 with Linux and in its status as the most popular version of X.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] By 2003, while the popularity of Linux (and hence the installed base of X) surged, X.Org remained inactive, and active development took place largely within XFree86.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] However, considerable dissent developed within XFree86.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The XFree86 project suffered from a perception of a far too cathedral-like development model; developers could not get CVS commit access and vendors had to maintain extensive patch sets.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] In March 2003, the XFree86 organization expelled Keith Packard, who had joined XFree86 after the end of the original MIT X Consortium, with considerable ill feeling.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] X.Org and XFree86 began discussing a reorganisation suited to properly nurturing the development of X.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Jim Gettys had been pushing strongly for an open development model since at least 2000.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Gettys, Packard and several others began discussing in detail the requirements for the effective governance of X with open development.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Finally, in an echo of the X11R6.4 licensing dispute, XFree86 released version 4.4 in February 2004 under a more restrictive license which many projects relying on X found unacceptable.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The added clause to the license was based on the original BSD license's advertising clause, which was viewed by the Free Software Foundation and Debian as incompatible with the GNU General Public License.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Other groups saw it as against the spirit of the original X.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Theo de Raadt of OpenBSD, for instance, threatened to fork XFree86 citing license concerns.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The license issue, combined with the difficulties in getting changes in, left many feeling the time was ripe for a fork.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] In early 2004, various people from X.Org and freedesktop.org formed the X.Org Foundation, and the Open Group gave it control of the `x.org` domain name.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] This marked a radical change in the governance of X.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Whereas the stewards of X since 1988 (including the prior X.Org) had been vendor organizations, the Foundation was led by software developers and used community development based on the bazaar model, which relies on outside involvement.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Membership was opened to individuals, with corporate membership being in the form of sponsorship.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Several major corporations such as Hewlett-Packard currently support the X.Org Foundation.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The Foundation takes an oversight role over X development: technical decisions are made on their merits by achieving rough consensus among community members.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Technical decisions are not made by the board of directors; in this sense, it is strongly modelled on the technically non-interventionist GNOME Foundation.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The Foundation released X11R6.7, the X.Org Server, in April 2004, based on XFree86 4.4RC2 with X11R6.6 changes merged.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Gettys and Packard had taken the last version of XFree86 under the old license and, by making a point of an open development model and retaining GPL compatibility, brought many of the old XFree86 developers on board.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] While X11 had received extensions such as OpenGL support during the 1990s, its architecture had remained fundamentally unchanged during the decade.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] In the early part of the 2000s, however, it was overhauled to resolve a number of problems that had surfaced over the years, including a "flawed" font architecture, a 2D graphics system "which had always been intended to be augmented and/or replaced", and latency issues.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] It added significant new features, including preliminary support for translucent windows and other sophisticated visual effects, screen magnifiers and thumbnailers, and facilities to integrate with 3D immersive display systems such as Sun's Project Looking Glass and the Croquet project.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] External applications called *compositing window managers* provide policy for the visual appearance.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] On 21 December 2005, X.Org released X11R6.9, the monolithic source tree for legacy users, and X11R7.0, the same source code separated into independent modules, each maintainable in separate projects.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The Foundation released X11R7.1 on 22 May 2006, about four months after 7.0, with considerable feature improvements.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] XFree86 development continued for a few more years, with 4.8.0 being released on 15 December 2008.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The proper names for the system are listed in the manual page as X; X Window System; X Version 11; X Window System, Version 11; or X11.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] A graphics device such as a computer graphics card or a computer motherboard's integrated graphics chipset.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] , or within a graphics device, some of which can render into more than one screen simultaneously, either viewable simultaneously or interchangeably.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] Interchangeable screens are often set up to be notionally left and right from one another, flipping from one to the next as the mouse pointer reaches the edge of the monitor.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] A collection of screens, often involving multiple monitors, generally configured to allow the mouse to move the pointer to any position within them.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] , simultaneously flipping all the monitors from showing the screens of one display to the screens in another.
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The term "display" should not be confused with the more specialized jargon "Zaphod display".
[src:x11-windowing/x-window-system] The latter is a rare configuration allowing multiple users of a single computer to each have an independent set of display, mouse, and keyboard, as though they were using separate computers, but at a lower per-seat cost.
